To replace custom tags like [url=https://google.com]Display Text[/url] with a proper <a> tag using jQuery, you can use a regular expression to parse the content and perform the replacement.

Here’s how you can do it:


---

jQuery Code to Replace [url] with <a> Tag

$(document).ready(function () {
    // Example content
    let content = "This is a [url=https://google.com]Google[/url] link.";

    // Replace custom [url] tags with <a> tags
    content = content.replace(/url=(.+?)(.+?)\/url/g, function (match, url, text) {
        return `<a href="${url}" target="_blank">${text}</a>`;
    });

    // Display the modified content
    $("#output").html(content);
});


---

Explanation

1. Regular Expression:

url=(.+?)(.+?)\/url

Matches [url=...]Display Text[/url] patterns.

(.*?) captures the URL and display text.




2. Replacement Function:

In the replace function, url and text are the captured groups.

The replacement string is <a href="${url}" target="_blank">${text}</a>.



3. Updating Content:

The modified content is inserted into an HTML element using $("#output").html(content).





---

Example HTML for Testing

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Replace Custom URL Tags</title>
  <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="output">
    This is a [url=https://google.com]Google[/url] link.
  </div>

